The paper deals with a graph-theoretic model for geometric milling problems, which is a natural fit for the computer science sub-categories of data structures (cs.DS) and computational geometry (cs.CG). The study of the parameterized complexity of the problem suggests that it could also fall under the categories of computational complexity (cs.CC) and graph theory (cs.GT). Additionally, the use of turn costs and the analysis of pathwidth could make it relevant to the sub-category of discrete mathematics (cs.DM).
